# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: leftist-heap
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] In computer science, a **binomial heap** is a data structure that acts as a priority queue.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] It is an example of a mergeable heap (also called meldable heap), as it supports merging two heaps in logarithmic time.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] It is implemented as a heap similar to a binary heap but using a special tree structure that is different from the complete binary trees used by binary heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Binomial heaps were invented in 1978 by Jean Vuillemin.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] A binomial tree of order k has $2^{k}$ nodes, and height k .
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] The name comes from the shape: a binomial tree of order k has ${\tbinom {k}{d}}$ nodes at depth d , a binomial coefficient.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Because of its structure, a binomial tree of order k can be constructed from two trees of order $k-1$ by attaching one of them as the leftmost child of the root of the other tree.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] This feature is central to the *merge* operation of a binomial heap, which is its major advantage over other conventional heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] The first property ensures that the root of each binomial tree contains the smallest key in the tree.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] It follows that the smallest key in the entire heap is one of the roots.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] The second property implies that a binomial heap with n nodes consists of at most $1+\log _{2}n$ binomial trees, where $\log _{2}$ is the binary logarithm.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] The number and orders of these trees are uniquely determined by the number of nodes n : there is one binomial tree for each nonzero bit in the binary representation of the number n .
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] For example, the decimal number 13 is 1101 in binary, $2^{3}+2^{2}+2^{0}$ , and thus a binomial heap with 13 nodes will consist of three binomial trees of orders 3, 2, and 0 (see figure below).
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] The number of different ways that n items with distinct keys can be arranged into a binomial heap equals the largest odd divisor of $n!$ .
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] If the n items are inserted into a binomial heap in a uniformly random order, each of these arrangements is equally likely.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Because no operation requires random access to the root nodes of the binomial trees, the roots of the binomial trees can be stored in a linked list, ordered by increasing order of the tree.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] These sibling pointers can be interpreted as the next pointers in a linked list of the children of each node, but with the opposite order from the linked list of roots: from largest to smallest order, rather than vice versa.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] This representation allows two trees of the same order to be linked together, making a tree of the next larger order, in constant time.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] The operation of **merging** two heaps is used as a subroutine in most other operations.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] A basic subroutine within this procedure merges pairs of binomial trees of the same order.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] This may be done by comparing the keys at the roots of the two trees (the smallest keys in both trees).
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] To merge two heaps more generally, the lists of roots of both heaps are traversed simultaneously in a manner similar to that of the merge algorithm, in a sequence from smaller orders of trees to larger orders.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] When only one of the two heaps being merged contains a tree of order j , this tree is moved to the output heap.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] When both of the two heaps contain a tree of order j , the two trees are merged to one tree of order $j+1$ so that the minimum-heap property is satisfied.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] It may later become necessary to merge this tree with some other tree of order $j+1$ in one of the two input heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] In the course of the algorithm, it will examine at most three trees of any order, two from the two heaps we merge and one composed of two smaller trees.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Because each binomial tree in a binomial heap corresponds to a bit in the binary representation of its size, there is an analogy between the merging of two heaps and the binary addition of the *sizes* of the two heaps, from right-to-left.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Whenever a carry occurs during addition, this corresponds to a merging of two binomial trees during the merge.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Each binomial tree's traversal during merge only involves roots, hence making the time taken at most order $\log _{2}n$ and therefore the running time is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] A variant of the binomial heap, the skew binomial heap, achieves constant worst case insertion time by using forests whose tree sizes are based on the skew binary number system rather than on the binary number system.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] To find the **minimum** element of the heap, find the minimum among the roots of the binomial trees.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] This can be done in $O(\log n)$ time, as there are just $O(\log n)$ tree roots to examine.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] By using a pointer to the binomial tree that contains the minimum element, the time for this operation can be reduced to $O(1)$ .
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] The pointer must be updated when performing any operation other than finding the minimum.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] This can be done in $O(\log n)$ time per update, without raising the overall asymptotic running time of any operation.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] To **delete the minimum element** from the heap, first find this element, remove it from the root of its binomial tree, and obtain a list of its child subtrees (which are each themselves binomial trees, of distinct orders).
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Transform this list of subtrees into a separate binomial heap by reordering them from smallest to largest order.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Then merge this heap with the original heap.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Since each root has at most $\log _{2}n$ children, creating this new heap takes time $O(\log n)$ .
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Merging heaps takes time $O(\log n)$ , so the entire delete minimum operation takes time $O(\log n)$ .
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] After **decreasing** the key of an element, it may become smaller than the key of its parent, violating the minimum-heap property.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] If this is the case, exchange the element with its parent, and possibly also with its grandparent, and so on, until the minimum-heap property is no longer violated.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Each binomial tree has height at most $\log _{2}n$ , so this takes $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] However, this operation requires that the representation of the tree include pointers from each node to its parent in the tree, somewhat complicating the implementation of other operations.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] To **delete** an element from the heap, decrease its key to negative infinity (or equivalently, to some value lower than any element in the heap) and then delete the minimum in the heap.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] For persistent heaps (not supporting *decrease-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-min* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-min* and *meld*.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-min* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:leftist-heap/binomial-heap] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *decrease-key* is not supported.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] In computer science, a **heap** is a tree-based data structure that satisfies the **heap property**: In a *max heap*, for any given node C, if P is the parent node of C, then the *key* (the *value*) of P is greater than or equal to the key of C.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] In a *min heap*, the key of P is less than or equal to the key of C.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] The node at the "top" of the heap (with no parents) is called the *root* node.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap is one maximally efficient implementation of an abstract data type called a priority queue, and in fact, priority queues are often referred to as "heaps", regardless of how they may be implemented.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] In a heap, the highest (or lowest) priority element is always stored at the root.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] However, a heap is not a sorted structure; it can be regarded as being partially ordered.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] A heap is a useful data structure when it is necessary to repeatedly remove the object with the highest (or lowest) priority, or when insertions need to be interspersed with removals of the root node.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] A common implementation of a heap is the binary heap, in which the tree is a complete binary tree (see figure).
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure, specifically the binary heap, was introduced by J.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] Williams in 1964, as a data structure for the heapsort sorting algorithm.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are also crucial in several efficient graph algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] When a heap is a complete binary tree, it has the smallest possible height—a heap with *N* nodes and *a* branches for each node always has log*a* *N* height.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] Note that, as shown in the graphic, there is no implied ordering between siblings or cousins and no implied sequence for an in-order traversal (as there would be in, e.g., a binary search tree).
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap relation mentioned above applies only between nodes and their parents, grandparents.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] The maximum number of children each node can have depends on the type of heap.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps are typically constructed in-place in the same array where the elements are stored, with their structure being implicit in the access pattern of the operations.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] Heaps differ in this way from other data structures with similar or in some cases better theoretic bounds such as radix trees in that they require no additional memory beyond that used for storing the keys.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] For a binary heap, in the array, the first index contains the root element.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] The next two indices of the array contain the root's children.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] The next four indices contain the four children of the root's two child nodes, and so on.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] Therefore, given a node at index i, its children are at indices ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠ and ⁠ $2i+2$ ⁠, and its parent is at index ⌊(*i*−1)/2⌋ in an array starting from index ⁠ 0 ⁠, or at ⁠ $2i$ ⁠, ⁠ $2i+1$ ⁠, and ⌊*i*/2⌋, respectively, in an array starting from ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] This simple indexing scheme makes it efficient to walk "up" or "down" the tree.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] Balancing a heap is done by sift-up or sift-down operations (swapping elements which are out of order).
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] As we can build a heap from an array without requiring extra memory (for the nodes, for example), heapsort can be used to sort an array in-place.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] After an element is inserted into or deleted from a heap, the heap property may be violated, and the heap must be re-balanced by swapping elements within the array.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] This is faster than a sequence of consecutive insertions into an originally empty heap, which is log-linear.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] *make-heap* is the operation of building a heap from a sequence of *n* unsorted elements.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] It can be done in *Θ*(*n*) time whenever *meld* runs in *O*(log *n*) time (where both complexities can be amortized).
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] Another algorithm achieves *Θ*(*n*) for binary heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] For persistent heaps (not supporting *increase-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-max* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-max* and *meld*.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-max* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *increase-key* is not supported.
[src:leftist-heap/heap-data-structure] The heap data structure has many applications.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] In computer science, a **leftist tree** or **leftist heap** is a priority queue implemented with a variant of a binary heap.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Every node x has an *s-value* which is the distance to the nearest leaf in subtree rooted at x.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] In contrast to a *binary heap*, a leftist tree attempts to be very unbalanced.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] In addition to the heap property, leftist trees are maintained so the right descendant of each node has the lower s-value.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The height-biased leftist tree was invented by Clark Allan Crane.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The name comes from the fact that the left subtree is usually taller than the right subtree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] When inserting a new node into a tree, a new one-node tree is created and merged into the existing tree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] To delete an item, it is replaced by the merge of its left and right sub-trees.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Both these operations take O(log *n*) time.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] For insertions, this is slower than Fibonacci heaps, which support insertion in O(1) (constant) amortized time, and O(log *n*) worst-case.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Leftist trees are advantageous because of their ability to merge quickly, compared to binary heaps which take Θ(*n*).
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] In almost all cases, the merging of skew heaps has better performance.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] However merging leftist heaps has worst-case O(log *n*) complexity while merging skew heaps has only amortized O(log *n*) complexity.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The usual leftist tree is a *height-biased* leftist tree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] However, other biases can exist, such as in the *weight-biased* leftist tree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The exact worst-case complexity of both types of leftist trees is 2 log2 *n*, counting comparisons.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The **s-value** (or **rank**) of a node is the distance from that node to the nearest empty position in the subtree rooted at that node.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Put another way, the s-value of a `null` child is implicitly zero.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Other nodes have an s-value equal to one more the minimum of their children's s-values.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, in the example at right, all nodes with at least one missing child have an s-value of 1, while node 4 has an s-value of 2, since its right child (8) has an s-value of 1.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Knowing the shortest path to the nearest missing leaf in the subtree rooted at *x* is exactly of *s*(*x*), every node at depth *s*(*x*)−1 or less has exactly 2 children since *s*(*x*) would have been less if not.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Meaning that the size of the tree rooted at *x* is at least $2^{s(x)}-1$ .
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, *s*(*x*) is at most $\log {(m+1)}$ , *m* being the number of nodes of the subtree rooted at *x*.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Most operations on a Height Biased Leftist Tree are done using the merge operation.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The merge operation takes two Min HBLTs as input and returns a Min HBLT containing all the nodes in the original Min HBLTs put together.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] If either of A or B is empty, the merge returns the other one.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] In case of Min HBLTs, assume we have two trees rooted at A and B where A.key $\leq$ B.key.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Otherwise we can swap A and B so that the condition above holds.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The merge is done recursively by merging B with A's right subtree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] This might change the S-value of A's right subtree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] To maintain the leftist tree property, after each merge is done, we check if the S-value of right subtree became bigger than the S-value of left subtree during the recursive merge calls.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] If so, we swap the right and left subtrees (If one child is missing, it should be the right one).
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Since we assumed that A's root is greater than B's, the heap property is also maintained.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] An example of how the merge operation in a leftist tree works is depicted.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] When the recursion unwinds, we swap left and right children if x.right.s_value > x.left.s_value for every node x.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] In this case we swapped the subtrees rooted at nodes with keys 7 and 10.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Insertion is done using the merge operation.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] An insertion of a node into an already existing Min HBLT, creates a HBLT tree of size one with that node and merges it with the existing tree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The Min element in a Min HBLT is the root.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, in order to delete the Min, the root is deleted and its subtrees are merged to form the new Min HBLT.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Initializing a height biased leftist tree is primarily done in one of two ways.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The first is to merge each node one at a time into one HBLT.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] This process is inefficient and takes O(*nlogn*) time.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The other approach is to use a queue to store each node and resulting tree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The first two items in the queue are removed, merged, and placed back into the queue.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] This can initialize a HBLT in O(*n*) time.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] This approach is detailed in the three diagrams supplied.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] A min height biased leftist tree is shown.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] To initialize a min HBLT, place each element to be added to the tree into a queue.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] In the example (see Part 1 to the left), the set of numbers [4, 8, 10, 9, 1, 3, 5, 6, 11] are initialized.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Each line of the diagram represents another cycle of the algorithm, depicting the contents of the queue.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The first five steps are easy to follow.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Notice that the freshly created HBLT is added to the end of the queue.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] In the fifth step, the first occurrence of an s-value greater than 1 occurs.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The sixth step shows two trees merged with each other, with predictable results.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] In part 2 a slightly more complex merge happens.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The tree with the lower value (tree x) has a right child, so merge must be called again on the subtree rooted by tree x's right child and the other tree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] After the merge with the subtree, the resulting tree is put back into tree x.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The s-value of the right child (s=2) is now greater than the s-value of the left child (s=1), so they must be swapped.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The s-value of the root node 4 is also now 2.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Here, we recursively call merge twice (each time with the right child 's subtree that is not grayed out).
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] This uses the same process described for part 2.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] If we have a pointer to a node x in a Min HBLT, we can delete it as follows: Replace the node x with the result of merging its two subtrees and update the s-values of the nodes on the path from x to the root, swapping the right and left subtrees if necessary to maintain the leftist tree property.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The upward traversal is continued until either we hit the root or the s-value does not change.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Since we are deleting an element, the S-values on the path traversed cannot be increased.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Every node that is already the right child of its parent and causes its parent's s-value to be decreased, will remain on the right.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Every node that is its parent's left child and causes the parent's s-value to be decreased has to be swapped with its right sibling if the s-value becomes lower than the current s-value of the right child.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Each node needs to have a pointer to its parent, so that we can traverse the path to the root updating the s-values.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] When the traversal ends at some node y, the nodes traversed all lie on the rightmost path rooted at node y.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] It follows that the number of nodes traversed is at most log(m), m being the size of the subtree rooted at y.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, this operation also takes O(lg m) to perform.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Leftist trees can also be weight biased.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] WBLTs ensure w(x.left) ≥ w(x.right) for all internal nodes x.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] WBLT operations ensure this invariant by swapping the children of a node when the right subtree outgrows the left one, just as in HBLT operations.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The merge operation in WBLTs can be done using a single top to bottom traversal since the number of nodes in the subtrees are known prior to recursive call to merge.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Thus, we can swap left and right subtrees if the total number of nodes in the right subtree and the tree to be merged is bigger than the number of nodes in the left subtree.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] This allows the operations be completed in a single path and so improves the time complexity of the operations by a constant factor.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] The merge operation is depicted in the graph below.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Insertions and deletion of the min element can be done in the same as for HBLTs using the merge operation.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] Although WBLTs outperform HBLTs in merge, insertion and deletion of the Min key by a constant factor, the *O*(log *n*) bound is not guaranteed when deleting an arbitrary element from WBLTs, since θ(*n*) nodes have to be traversed.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] If this was an HBLT, then deleting the leaf node with key 60 would take *O*(1) time and updating the s-values is not needed since the length of rightmost path for all the nodes does not change.
[src:leftist-heap/leftist-tree] But in an WBLT tree, we have to update the weight of each node back to the root, which takes *O*(*n*) worst case.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In computer science, a **priority queue** is an abstract data type similar to a regular queue where each element has an associated priority determining its order of service.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Priority queue serves highest priority items first.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Priority values have to be instances of an ordered data type, and higher priority can be given either to the lesser or to the greater values with respect to the given order relation.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For example, in the Java standard library, the PriorityQueue class considers the lowest element with respect to their order as having the highest priority.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] While priority queues are often implemented using heaps, they are conceptually distinct.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue can be implemented with a heap or with other methods; just as a list can be implemented with a linked list or with an array.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Stacks and queues can be implemented as particular kinds of priority queues, with the priority determined by the order in which the elements are inserted.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In a stack, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically increasing; thus, the last element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In a queue, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically decreasing; thus, the first element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In some implementations, if two elements have the same priority, they are served in the same order in which they were enqueued.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In other implementations, the order of elements with the same priority is undefined.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] One can create a simple, but inefficient priority queue in a number of ways.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] These naive implementations can demonstrate the expected behaviour of a priority queue in a simpler manner.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] To improve performance, priority queues are typically based on a heap, giving $O(\log n)$ performance for inserts and removals, and $O(n)$ to build the heap initially from a set of n elements.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Variants of the basic heap data structure such as pairing heaps or Fibonacci heaps can provide better bounds for some operations.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] From a space-complexity standpoint, using self-balancing binary search tree with linked list takes more storage, since it requires storing extra references to other nodes.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] From a computational-complexity standpoint, priority queues are congruent to sorting algorithms.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The section on the equivalence of priority queues and sorting algorithms, below, describes how efficient sorting algorithms can create efficient priority queues.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] There are several specialized heap data structures that either supply additional operations or outperform heap-based implementations for specific types of keys, specifically integer keys.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For applications that do many "peek" operations for every "`extract-min`" operation, the time complexity for peek actions can be reduced to $O(1)$ in all tree and heap implementations by caching the highest priority element after every insertion and removal.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For insertion, this adds at most a constant cost, since the newly inserted element is compared only to the previously cached minimum element.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For deletion, this at most adds an additional "peek" cost, which is typically cheaper than the deletion cost, so overall time complexity is not significantly impacted.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Monotone priority queues are specialized queues that are optimized for the case where no item is ever inserted that has a lower priority (in the case of min-heap) than any item previously extracted.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This restriction is met by several practical applications of priority queues.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The semantics of priority queues naturally suggest a sorting method: insert all the elements to be sorted into a priority queue, and sequentially remove them; they will come out in sorted order.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This is actually the procedure used by several sorting algorithms, once the layer of abstraction provided by the priority queue is removed.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] A sorting algorithm can also be used to implement a priority queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For example, if one has an $O(n\log n)$ sort algorithm, one can create a priority queue with $O(1)$ pulling and $O(\log n)$ insertion.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is often considered to be a "container data structure".
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The Standard Template Library (STL), and the C++ 1998 standard, specifies std::priority_queue as one of the STL container adaptor class templates.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] However, it does not specify how two elements with same priority should be served, and indeed, common implementations will not return them according to their order in the queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Unlike actual STL containers, it does not allow iteration of its elements (it strictly adheres to its abstract data type definition).
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] STL also has utility functions for manipulating another random-access container as a binary max-heap.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The Boost libraries also have an implementation in the library heap.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Python's heapq module implements a binary min-heap on top of a list.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Java's library contains a `PriorityQueue` (`java.util.PriorityQueue`) class, which implements a min-priority-queue as a binary heap.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] .NET's library contains a System.Collections.Generic.PriorityQueue class, which implements an array-backed, quaternary min-heap.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Scala's library contains a scala.collection.mutable.PriorityQueue class, which implements a max-priority-queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Go's library contains a container/heap module, which implements a min-heap on top of any compatible data structure.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Rust's standard library contains a std::collections::BinaryHeap struct, which implements a priority queue with a binary heap.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The Standard PHP Library extension contains the class SplPriorityQueue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Apple's Core Foundation framework contains a CFBinaryHeap structure, which implements a min-heap.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Priority queuing can be used to manage limited resources such as bandwidth on a transmission line from a network router.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In the event of outgoing traffic queuing due to insufficient bandwidth, all other queues can be halted to send the traffic from the highest priority queue upon arrival.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that the prioritized traffic (such as real-time traffic, e.g. an RTP stream of a VoIP connection) is forwarded with the least delay and the least likelihood of being rejected due to a queue reaching its maximum capacity.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] All other traffic can be handled when the highest priority queue is empty.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Another approach used is to send disproportionately more traffic from higher priority queues.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Many modern protocols for local area networks also include the concept of priority queues at the media access control (MAC) sub-layer to ensure that high-priority applications (such as VoIP or IPTV) experience lower latency than other applications which can be served with best-effort service.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Examples include IEEE 802.11e (an amendment to IEEE 802.11 which provides quality of service) and ITU-T G.hn (a standard for high-speed local area network using existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables).
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Usually a limitation (policer) is set to limit the bandwidth that traffic from the highest priority queue can take, in order to prevent high priority packets from choking off all other traffic.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This limit is usually never reached due to high level control instances such as the Cisco Callmanager, which can be programmed to inhibit calls which would exceed the programmed bandwidth limit.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Another use of a priority queue is to manage the events in a discrete event simulation.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The events are added to the queue with their simulation time used as the priority.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The execution of the simulation proceeds by repeatedly pulling the top of the queue and executing the event thereon.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] When the graph is stored in the form of adjacency list or matrix, priority queue can be used to extract minimum efficiently when implementing Dijkstra's algorithm, although one also needs the ability to alter the priority of a particular vertex in the priority queue efficiently.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] If instead, a graph is stored as node objects, and priority-node pairs are inserted into a heap, altering the priority of a particular vertex is not necessary if one tracks visited nodes.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Once a node is visited, if it comes up in the heap again (having had a lower priority number associated with it earlier), it is popped-off and ignored.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Huffman coding requires one to repeatedly obtain the two lowest-frequency trees.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue is one method of doing this.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Best-first search algorithms, like the A* search algorithm, find the shortest path between two vertices or nodes of a weighted graph, trying out the most promising routes first.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] A priority queue (also known as the *fringe*) is used to keep track of unexplored routes; the one for which the estimate (a lower bound in the case of A*) of the total path length is smallest is given highest priority.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] If memory limitations make best-first search impractical, variants like the SMA* algorithm can be used instead, with a double-ended priority queue to allow removal of low-priority items.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The Real-time Optimally Adapting Meshes (ROAM) algorithm computes a dynamically changing triangulation of a terrain.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] It works by splitting triangles where more detail is needed and merging them where less detail is needed.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm assigns each triangle in the terrain a priority, usually related to the error decrease if that triangle would be split.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm uses two priority queues, one for triangles that can be split and another for triangles that can be merged.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In each step the triangle from the split queue with the highest priority is split, or the triangle from the merge queue with the lowest priority is merged with its neighbours.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Using min heap priority queue in Prim's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a connected and undirected graph, one can achieve a good running time.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This min heap priority queue uses the min heap data structure which supports operations such as `insert`, `minimum`, `extract-min`, `decrease-key`.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In this implementation, the weight of the edges is used to decide the priority of the vertices.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Lower the weight, higher the priority and higher the weight, lower the priority.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Parallelization can be used to speed up priority queues, but requires some changes to the priority queue interface.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The reason for such changes is that a sequential update usually only has ${\textstyle O(1)}$ or ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost, and there is no practical gain to parallelize such an operation.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] One possible change is to allow the concurrent access of multiple processors to the same priority queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The second possible change is to allow batch operations that work on ${\textstyle k}$ elements, instead of just one element.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For example, `extractMin` will remove the first ${\textstyle k}$ elements with the highest priority.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] If the priority queue allows concurrent access, multiple processes can perform operations concurrently on that priority queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] First of all, the definition of the semantics of the individual operations is no longer obvious.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For example, if two processes want to extract the element with the highest priority, should they get the same element or different ones?
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This restricts parallelism on the level of the program using the priority queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In addition, because multiple processes have access to the same element, this leads to contention.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The concurrent access to a priority queue can be implemented on a Concurrent Read, Concurrent Write (CRCW) PRAM model.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In the following the priority queue is implemented as a skip list.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In addition, an atomic synchronization primitive, CAS, is used to make the skip list lock-free.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The nodes of the skip list consists of a unique key, a priority, an array of pointers, for each level, to the next nodes and a `delete` mark.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The `delete` mark marks if the node is about to be deleted by a process.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This ensures that other processes can react to the deletion appropriately.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] If the concurrent access to a priority queue is allowed, conflicts may arise between two processes.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For example, a conflict arises if one process is trying to insert a new node, but at the same time another process is about to delete the predecessor of that node.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] There is a risk that the new node is added to the skip list, yet it is not longer reachable.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In this setting, operations on a priority queue is generalized to a batch of ${\textstyle k}$ elements.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_extract-min` deletes the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the priority queue and returns those.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In a shared-memory setting, the parallel priority queue can be easily implemented using parallel binary search trees and join-based tree algorithms.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] In particular, `k_extract-min` corresponds to a *split* on the binary search tree that has ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost and yields a tree that contains the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] `k_insert` can be applied by a *union* of the original priority queue and the batch of insertions.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] If the batch is already sorted by the key, `k_insert` has ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}}))}$ cost.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Otherwise, we need to first sort the batch, so the cost will be ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}})+k\log k)=O(k\log n)}$ .
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Other operations for priority queue can be applied similarly.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] For instance, `k_decrease-key` can be done by first applying `difference` and then `union`, which first deletes the elements and then inserts them back with the updated keys.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] All these operations are highly parallel, and the theoretical and practical efficiency can be found in related research papers.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The rest of this section discusses a queue-based algorithm on distributed memory.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] We assume each processor has its own local memory and a local (sequential) priority queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The elements of the global (parallel) priority queue are distributed across all processors.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] A `k_insert` operation assigns the elements uniformly random to the processors which insert the elements into their local queues.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Note that single elements can still be inserted into the queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Using this strategy the global smallest elements are in the union of the local smallest elements of every processor with high probability.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Thus each processor holds a representative part of the global priority queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This property is used when `k_extract-min` is executed, as the smallest ${\textstyle m}$ elements of each local queue are removed and collected in a result set.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The elements in the result set are still associated with their original processor.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The number of elements ${\textstyle m}$ that is removed from each local queue depends on ${\textstyle k}$ and the number of processors ${\textstyle p}$ .
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] By parallel selection the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the result set are determined.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] With high probability these are the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] If not, ${\textstyle m}$ elements are again removed from each local queue and put into the result set.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This is done until the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements are in the result set.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Now these ${\textstyle k}$ elements can be returned.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] All other elements of the result set are inserted back into their local queues.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The running time of `k_extract-min` is expected ${\textstyle O({\frac {k}{p}}\log(n))}$ , where ${\textstyle k=\Omega (p\cdot \log(p))}$ and ${\textstyle n}$ is the size of the priority queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The priority queue can be further improved by not moving the remaining elements of the result set directly back into the local queues after a `k_extract-min` operation.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] This saves moving elements back and forth all the time between the result set and the local queues.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] By removing several elements at once a considerable speedup can be reached.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] But not all algorithms can use this kind of priority queue.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] Dijkstra's algorithm for example can not work on several nodes at once.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] The algorithm takes the node with the smallest distance from the priority queue and calculates new distances for all its neighbor nodes.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] If you would take out ${\textstyle k}$ nodes, working at one node could change the distance of another one of the ${\textstyle k}$ nodes.
[src:leftist-heap/priority-queue] So using k-element operations destroys the label setting property of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] A **skew heap** (or **self-adjusting heap**) is a heap data structure implemented as a binary tree.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] Skew heaps are advantageous because of their ability to merge more quickly than binary heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] In contrast with binary heaps, there are no structural constraints, so there is no guarantee that the height of the tree is logarithmic.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] A skew heap is a self-adjusting form of a leftist heap which attempts to maintain balance by unconditionally swapping all nodes in the merge path when merging two heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] (The merge operation is also used when adding and removing values.) With no structural constraints, it may seem that a skew heap would be horribly inefficient.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] However, amortized complexity analysis can be used to demonstrate that all operations on a skew heap can be done in O(log *n*).
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] In fact, with ${\textstyle \varphi ={\frac {1+{\sqrt {5}}}{2}}}$ denoting the golden ratio, the exact amortized complexity is known to be logφ *n* (approximately 1.44 log2 *n*).
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] Alternatively, there is a non-recursive approach which is more wordy, and does require some sorting at the outset.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] Adding a value to a skew heap is like merging a tree with one node together with the original tree.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] Removing the first value in a heap can be accomplished by removing the root and merging its child subtrees.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] In many functional languages, skew heaps become extremely simple to implement.
[src:leftist-heap/skew-heap] Here is a complete sample implementation in Haskell.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] In computer science, a **weak heap** is a data structure for priority queues, combining features of the binary heap and binomial heap.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] It can be stored in an array as an implicit binary tree like a binary heap, and has the efficiency guarantees of binomial heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] A weak heap is most easily understood as a heap-ordered multi-way tree stored as a binary tree using the "right-child left-sibling" convention.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] In the multi-way tree, and assuming a max-heap, each parent's key is greater than or equal to (≥) all the child keys (and thus, by induction, all members of the subtree).
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] The last condition is a consequence of the fact that an implicit binary tree is a complete binary tree.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] The structure of this tree maps very neatly onto the traditional 1-based (Ahnentafel) implicit binary tree arrangement, where node k has a next sibling (left child) numbered 2*k* and a first child (right child) numbered 2*k* + 1, by adding an additional root numbered 0.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] This root has no siblings, only a first child, which is node 1 (2×0 + 1).
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] This structure is very similar to that of a binomial heap, with a tree of height h being composed of a root plus trees of heights *h* − 1, *h* − 2, ..., 1.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] A perfect (no missing leaves) weak heap with 2*n* elements is exactly isomorphic to a binomial heap of the same size, but the two algorithms handle sizes which are not a power of 2 differently: a binomial heap uses multiple perfect trees, while a weak heap uses a single imperfect tree.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Weak heaps require the ability to exchange the left and right children (and associated subtrees) of a node.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] In an explicit (pointer-based) representation of the tree, this is straightforward.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] In an implicit (array) representation, this requires one "reverse bit" per internal node to indicate which child is considered the left child.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] A weak heap is thus not a strictly implicit data structure since it requires *O*(*n*) additional space (⁠1/2⁠ bit per node).
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] However, it is often possible to find space for this extra bit within the node structure, such as by tagging a pointer which is already present.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] In the implicit binary tree, node k with reverse bit *rk* has parent ⌊⁠*k*/2⁠⌋, left child 2*k* + *rk*, and right child 2*k* + 1 − *rk*.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Viewed as a multi-way tree, each node in a weak heap is linked to two others: a "next sibling" and a "first child".
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] In the implicit tree, the links are fixed, so *which* of the two links is the sibling and which the first child is indicated by the reverse bit.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Note that *every* node in a weak heap can be considered the root of a smaller weak heap by ignoring its next sibling.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Nodes with no first child are automatically valid weak heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] A node of height h has *h* − 1 children: a first child of height *h* − 1, a second child of height *h* − 2, and so on to the last child of height 1.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] These may be found by following the first child link and then successive next sibling links.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] It also has next siblings of height *h* − 1, *h* − 2, etc.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] A node's parent in the multi-way tree is called its "distinguished ancestor".
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] To find this in the binary tree, find the node's binary parent.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] If the node is the right child (first child), the parent is the distinguished ancestor.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] If the node is the left child (next sibling), its distinguished ancestor is the same as its binary parent's.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] In the implicit tree, finding the binary parent is easy, but its reverse bit must be consulted to determine which type of child the node is.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Although the distinguished ancestor may be log2*n* levels high in the tree, the *average* distance is 2.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] (It's at least 1, and half of the time we recurse, so *D* = 1 + *D*/2, meaning that *D* = 2.) Thus, even a simple iterative algorithm for finding the distinguished ancestor is sufficient.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Like binomial heaps, the fundamental operation on weak heaps is merging two heaps of equal height h, to make a weak heap of height *h*+1.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] This requires exactly one comparison, between the roots.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Whichever root is greater (assuming a max-heap) is the final root.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Its first child is the losing root, which retains its children (right subtree).
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] The winning root's children are installed as siblings of the losing root.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] This operation can be performed on the implicit tree structure because the heaps being merged are never arbitrary.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] At the beginning, the heap invariants apply everywhere *except* possibly between the first root and its distinguished ancestor.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] All *other* nodes are less than or equal to their distinguished ancestors.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] (The first root is greater.) The first root's binary children (first child and next sibling) are exchanged (using the reverse bit), and then the first root and its distinguished ancestor are exchanged (by copying).
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] The second case works because, in the multi-way tree, each node keeps its children with it.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] The first root is promoted up the tree because it is greater than its distinguished ancestor.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Thus, it is safely greater than all of the ancestor's previous children.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] The previous ancestor, however, is not a safe parent for the first root's old children, because it is less than the first root and so it's not guaranteed to be greater than or equal to all of its children.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] By swapping the binary children, the appropriate subset of the demoted ancestor's old children (which are safely less than or equal to it) are demoted with it.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] The demoted ancestor's new siblings are the first root's old children, promoted, which are safely less than or equal to the promoted first root.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] After this operation, it is uncertain whether the invariant is maintained between the new distinguished ancestor and *its* distinguished ancestor, so the operation is repeated until the root is reached.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Weak heaps may be used to sort an array, in essentially the same way as a conventional heapsort.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] First, a weak heap is built out of all of the elements of the array, and then the root is repeatedly exchanged with the last element, which is sifted down to its proper place.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] A weak heap of n elements can be formed in *n* − 1 merges.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] It can be done on various orders, but a simple bottom-up implementation works from the end of the array to the beginning, merging each node with its distinguished ancestor.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Note that *finding* the distinguished ancestor is simplified because the reverse bits in all parents of the heaps being merged are unmodified from their initial state ("not reversed"), and so do not need to be consulted.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] As with heapsort, if the array to be sorted is larger than the CPU cache, performance is improved if subtrees are merged as soon as two of the same size become available, rather than merging all subtrees on one level before proceeding to the next.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Sifting down in a weak heap can be done in *h* = ⌈log2*n*⌉ comparisons, as opposed to 2 log2*n* for a binary heap, or 1.5 log2*n* for the "bottom-up heapsort" variant.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] This is done by "merging up": after swapping the root with the last element of the heap, find the last (height 1) child of the root.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Merge this with the root (its distinguished ancestor), resulting in a valid height-2 heap at the global root.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Then go to the previous sibling (binary parent) of the last merged node, and merge again.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Repeat until the root is reached, when it will be correct for the complete tree.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] In a weak max-heap, the maximum value can be found (in constant time) as the value associated with the root node; similarly, in a weak min-heap, the minimum value can be found at the root.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] As with binary heaps, weak heaps can support the typical operations of a priority queue data structure: insert, delete-min, delete, or decrease-key, in logarithmic time per operation.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Sifting up is done using the same process as in binary heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] The new node is added at the leaf level, then compared with its distinguished ancestor and swapped if necessary (the merge operation).
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] This is repeated until no more swaps are necessary or the root is reached.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Variants of the weak heap structure allow constant amortized time insertions and decrease-keys, matching the time for Fibonacci heaps.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] Weak heaps were introduced by Dutton (1993), as part of a variant heap sort algorithm that (unlike the standard heap sort using binary heaps) could be used to sort n items using only *n* log2*n* + *O*(*n*) comparisons.
[src:leftist-heap/weak-heap] They were later investigated as a more generally applicable priority queue data structure.
